.TH "INTEGRITYVIOLATIONREPORTBODY" "3JS" "November 30, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
IntegrityViolationReportBody \- IntegrityViolationReportBody
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]Secure context:\f[R] This feature is available only in secure
contexts (HTTPS).
.PP
The \f[CR]IntegrityViolationReportBody\f[R] dictionary is an extension
of the Reporting API that represents the body of an Integrity Policy
violation report.
.PP
Integrity violation reports can be reported to reporting server
endpoints or via a \f[CR]ReportingObserver\f[R].
They have a \f[CR]type\f[R] of \f[CR]\(dqintegrity\-violation\(dq\f[R],
a \f[CR]url\f[R] indicating the document that contains the violation,
and a \f[CR]body\f[R] property that is an object matching this
dictionary.
.SH INSTANCE PROPERTIES
.TP
\f[B]blockedURL\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
A string representing the URL of the resource blocked by an enforced
integrity policy (or just reported for a reportOnly policy).
.TP
\f[B]documentURL\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
A string representing the URL of the document that is attempting to load
the resource.
.TP
\f[B]destination\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
A string indicating the \f[CR]Request.destination\f[R] of the resource
that was blocked.
This can currently only be \f[CR]\(dqscript\(dq\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]reportOnly\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
A boolean: \f[CR]false\f[R] if the policy was enforced, and
\f[CR]true\f[R] if the violation was only reported.
.SH DESCRIPTION
Integrity Policy violations are reported when a document attempts to
load a resource that does not meet the Subresource Integrity guarantees
of a policy set using either the \f[CR]Integrity\-Policy\f[R] or
\f[CR]Integrity\-Policy\-Report\-Only\f[R] HTTP headers.
.PP
Specifically, a report is sent when a document attempts to load a
\f[CR]<script>\f[R] resource (or other request destination listed in the
policy) that does not have valid integrity metadata, or to make a
request in no\-cors mode.
.PP
Violation reports may be obtained in a violating document using a
\f[CR]ReportingObserver\f[R] callback (defined in the
\f[CR]ReportingObserver()\f[R] constructor), filtering on report objects
that have a \f[CR]type\f[R] of \f[CR]\(dqintegrity\-violation\(dq\f[R].
.PP
Violation reports may also be sent as JSON objects in \f[CR]POST\f[R]
requests to the \f[CR]endpoints\f[R] specified in the
\f[CR]Integrity\-Policy\f[R] and
\f[CR]Integrity\-Policy\-Report\-Only\f[R] headers.
The JSON report objects are a serialization of the reports returned in
the \f[CR]ReportingObserver\f[R], and therefore also have a
\f[CR]type\f[R] of \f[CR]\(dqintegrity\-violation\(dq\f[R], and a
\f[CR]body\f[R] property that is a serialization of this object.
Note that endpoint values set in the policy must map to identifiers set
using the \f[CR]Reporting\-Endpoints\f[R] header.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Reporting using the API
This example shows how you can obtain Integrity Policy violation reports
using a \f[CR]ReportingObserver\f[R].
.PP
First we set a page\(cqs integrity policy using the
\f[CR]Integrity\-Policy\f[R].
The policy below reports and blocks resource loading of any
\f[CR]<script>\f[R] element or \f[CR]HTMLScriptElement\f[R] object that
does not specify an \f[CR]integrity\f[R] attribute, or when a script
resource is requested in no\-cors mode.
Note that for this example we\(cqre only interested in reporting the
violations using the API, so we\(cqre omitting the reporting endpoints:
.IP
.EX
Integrity\-Policy: blocked\-destinations=(script)
.EE
.PP
Next, we\(cqll assume that our page includes the following element to
load a script.
Because we want to trigger a violation, it omits the
\f[CR]integrity\f[R] attribute used to check the script matches our
expected version.
We could also omit the \f[CR]cross\-origin\f[R] attribute so the request
is sent in \f[CR]no\-cors\f[R] mode.
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]script\f[R]
  src=\(dqhttps://example.com/example\-framework.js\(dq
  crossorigin=\(dqanonymous\(dq></\f[B]script\f[R]>
.EE
.RS
.PP
\f[B]Note:\f[R] A script that complies with the policy might look like
this:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]script\f[R]
  src=\(dqhttps://example.com/example\-framework.js\(dq
  integrity=\(dqsha384\-oqVuAfXRKap7fdgcCY5uykM6+R9GqQ8K/uxy9rx7HNQlGYl1kPzQho1wx4JwY8wC\(dq
  crossorigin=\(dqanonymous\(dq></\f[B]script\f[R]>
.EE
.RE
.PP
To observe violations within the page, we construct a new
\f[CR]ReportingObserver\f[R] object to listen for reports with the type
\f[CR]\(dqintegrity\-violation\(dq\f[R], passing a callback that will
receive and log the reports.
This code needs to be loaded before the script that causes the
violation, in the same page:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] observer = \f[B]new\f[R] ReportingObserver(
  (reports, observer) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
    reports.forEach((violation) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
      console.log(violation);
      console.log(JSON.stringify(violation));
    });
  },
  {
    types: [\(dqintegrity\-violation\(dq],
    buffered: \f[B]true\f[R],
  },
);

observer.observe();
.EE
.PP
Above, we log each violation report object and a JSON\-string version of
the object, which might look similar to the object below.
.IP
.EX
{
  \(dqtype\(dq: \(dqintegrity\-violation\(dq,
  \(dqurl\(dq: \(dqhttps://example.com\(dq,
  \(dqbody\(dq: {
    \(dqdocumentURL\(dq: \(dqhttps://example.com\(dq,
    \(dqblockedURL\(dq: \(dqhttps://example.com/example\-framework.js\(dq,
    \(dqdestination\(dq: \(dqscript\(dq,
    \(dqreportOnly\(dq: \f[B]false\f[R]
  }
}
.EE
.SS Sending a report to a reporting endpoint
Configuring a web page to send an Integrity Policy violation report to a
reporting server endpoint is very similar to the previous example.
.PP
The main difference is that we need to specify one or more reporting
endpoints where we want the reports to be sent, using the
\f[CR]Reporting\-Endpoints\f[R] response header, and then reference
these in the \f[CR]endpoints\f[R] field when setting the policy.
.PP
You can see this below, where we first define two endpoints \(em
\f[CR]integrity\-endpoint\f[R] and
\f[CR]backup\-integrity\-endpoint\f[R] \(em and then reference them in
our policy:
.IP
.EX
Reporting\-Endpoints: integrity\-endpoint=https://example.com/integrity, backup\-integrity\-endpoint=https://report\-provider.example/integrity
Integrity\-Policy: blocked\-destinations=(script), endpoints=(integrity\-endpoint, backup\-integrity\-endpoint)
.EE
.PP
We can trigger a violation by loading an external script from the page
that does not meet the subresource integrity guidelines.
Just to differ from the previous example, here we send the request in
\f[CR]no\-cors\f[R] mode:
.IP
.EX
<\f[B]script\f[R]
  src=\(dqhttps://example.com/example\-framework.js\(dq
  integrity=\(dqsha384\-oqVuAfXRKap7fdgcCY5uykM6+R9GqQ8K/uxy9rx7HNQlGYl1kPzQho1wx4JwY8wC\(dq></\f[B]script\f[R]>
.EE
.PP
The violation report will then be sent to the indicated endpoint as a
JSON file.
As you can see from the example below, the \f[CR]type\f[R] is
\f[CR]\(dqintegrity\-violation\(dq\f[R] and the \f[CR]body\f[R] property
is a serialization of this \f[CR]IntegrityViolationReportBody\f[R]
object:
.PP
The report in this case would look the same as our JSON report in the
previous example.
.IP
.EX
{
  \(dqtype\(dq: \(dqintegrity\-violation\(dq,
  \(dqurl\(dq: \(dqhttps://example.com\(dq,
  \(dqbody\(dq: {
    \(dqdocumentURL\(dq: \(dqhttps://example.com\(dq,
    \(dqblockedURL\(dq: \(dqhttps://example.com/example\-framework.js\(dq,
    \(dqdestination\(dq: \(dqscript\(dq,
    \(dqreportOnly\(dq: \f[B]false\f[R]
  }
}
.EE
